# accepted-coverage-gaps.yaml — what cannot be tested in this setup, and why.
#
# Every entry is a coverage gap treated as ACCEPTED: as long as an entry exists,
# the tool will not re-report that gap on every run. To stop accepting one (it
# became testable — you added the credential, enabled the flag, wired the
# service), delete it. Version control records who changed what, and when.
#
#   gap:     what cannot be exercised here — the specific surface or capability
#            left untested. (max 1000 runes)
#   reason:  why it is structurally untestable in THIS setup — prod-only behavior,
#            external infra/secrets you don't have, a licensed build you can't
#            produce. Be specific enough that a reviewer can challenge it.
#
# Only genuinely unfixable gaps belong here. A gap you could close by adding a
# fixture, credential, or flag is work to do — not a gap to accept. Broad entries
# hide real blind spots.
#
# This file accumulates across runs and is APPEND-ONLY. Anyone updating it — tool
# or human — must read it first, keep every existing entry, and only append;
# never rewrite, reorder, or drop entries. There is no generator for it (it is
# authored judgment, not derived data), so a clobbered entry is gone for good.
# COMMIT it to git — that is your history, your review trail, and your undo.
#
# Create `accepted-coverage-gaps.yaml` next to this file, carrying this header
# into it so its rules travel with the data.

accepted_coverage_gaps:
  - gap: "SSO login enforcement"
    reason: "Local and staging use password login; the SSO provider isn't wired here, so enforcement can't be exercised."
  - gap: "Payment callback replay"
    reason: "Staging provides no signed historical callbacks from the payment provider, so replay can't be reproduced."
  - gap: "Final inbox email delivery"
    reason: "The test environment captures outbound email metadata but not real inbox delivery events."

# Too broad — these hide real blind spots:
#   - gap: "Admin coverage"
#   - gap: "Anything needing credentials"
